            "role": "assistant",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "Centralia, Pennsylvania is special because it’s a near–ghost town that was effectively erased by an **underground coal-seam mine fire** that has been burning beneath it **since May 1962**. ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centralia_mine_fire))\n\nWhat makes it notable:\n\n- **A decades-long underground fire**: The coal fire spread through abandoned mine workings under/around the town and is expected to continue for a very long time (often cited as potentially centuries). ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centralia_mine_fire))  \n- **Mass evacuation and condemnation**: As conditions worsened (ground subsidence, gases, heat), the state used **eminent domain** and condemned properties, leading almost everyone to leave. ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centralia%2C_Pennsylvania))  \n- **One of Pennsylvania’s smallest municipalities**: Centralia’s population collapsed to just a handful of residents (Wikipedia lists **5 residents in 2020**)—making it famous as a “modern” American ghost town. ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centralia%2C_Pennsylvania))  \n- **The “Graffiti Highway” (now mostly gone/buried)**: A closed, damaged section of old Route 61 became a well-known graffiti spot and tourist draw until it was **covered/buried around 2020** to discourage visits. ([atlasobscura.com](https://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/centralia-graffiti-highway-buried))",
